00:05:21.220 --> 00:05:25.780
So I wanted to pick up
the treatment there.

00:05:25.780 --> 00:05:28.690
So what's the whole issue
behind line defects?

00:05:28.690 --> 00:05:33.790
Well, what line defects do is
they explain this anomalous

00:05:33.790 --> 00:05:37.496
behavior where the measured
value of yield strength--

00:05:42.630 --> 00:05:45.900
so I'm going to write
sigma y; sigma is

00:05:45.900 --> 00:05:49.350
the symbol for strength.

00:05:49.350 --> 00:05:58.060
the yield strength as measured
is on the order of only about

00:05:58.060 --> 00:06:01.120
1/10 of the theoretical value.

00:06:01.120 --> 00:06:05.010
It's only about 1/10 of the
theoretical value for the

00:06:05.010 --> 00:06:06.280
yield strength.

00:06:06.280 --> 00:06:07.200
You might, say, wait a minute.

00:06:07.200 --> 00:06:09.020
How do you get that
theoretical value?

00:06:09.020 --> 00:06:10.860
You can calculate this.

00:06:10.860 --> 00:06:12.100
Not too badly.

00:06:12.100 --> 00:06:16.090
If I take a look at a system of
atoms, and this could be a

00:06:16.090 --> 00:06:19.130
metallic crystal, you could
argue that there are metallic

00:06:19.130 --> 00:06:22.360
bonds between all of these
atoms. And if what I wanted to

00:06:22.360 --> 00:06:25.270
do to shear something--

00:06:25.270 --> 00:06:27.610
so this is the yield strength
for shear--

00:06:27.610 --> 00:06:31.620
if I wanted to shear the top
plane of atoms versus the

00:06:31.620 --> 00:06:34.190
bottom plane of atoms, can
you see that to a first

00:06:34.190 --> 00:06:37.170
approximation, the energy
required would be the energy

00:06:37.170 --> 00:06:38.780
to break each one
of these bonds?

00:06:38.780 --> 00:06:41.930
Because I have to break the bond
to release the plane and

00:06:41.930 --> 00:06:43.180
then move it.

00:06:43.180 --> 00:06:45.340
So if you make an estimation
on the

00:06:45.340 --> 00:06:46.590
basis of bond strength--

00:06:49.690 --> 00:06:56.990
so you take individual bond
strength times bond density or

00:06:56.990 --> 00:06:58.730
bond concentration.

00:06:58.730 --> 00:07:00.620
When I say density, I don't
necessarily mean

00:07:00.620 --> 00:07:01.760
mass per unit volume.

00:07:01.760 --> 00:07:03.910
I could mean bonds
per unit area.

00:07:03.910 --> 00:07:05.550
You saw your homework
questions.

00:07:05.550 --> 00:07:08.410
How many atoms per
unit length?

00:07:08.410 --> 00:07:10.210
And we said what's the
linear density?

00:07:10.210 --> 00:07:11.530
And some people were saying,
but density is

00:07:11.530 --> 00:07:12.460
mass per unit volume.

00:07:12.460 --> 00:07:15.370
No, I'm counting atoms
per unit length.

00:07:15.370 --> 00:07:17.940
Open your mind, OK?

00:07:17.940 --> 00:07:20.060
So bond strength, what's
bond density?

00:07:20.060 --> 00:07:22.460
That's atoms per unit area.

00:07:22.460 --> 00:07:25.380
So we can calculate this
and we're way off.

00:07:25.380 --> 00:07:28.090
We're way off by about
a factor of 10.

00:07:28.090 --> 00:07:30.820
So it was the dislocation
that allowed us to

00:07:30.820 --> 00:07:32.650
explain why this happens.

00:07:32.650 --> 00:07:37.870
And it was the work of two
scientists, one by the name of

00:07:37.870 --> 00:07:44.490
Orowan in Hungary and
Taylor in the UK.

00:07:44.490 --> 00:07:49.290
Orowan, after World War II,
went to the UK and then

00:07:49.290 --> 00:07:50.755
ultimately came to MIT.

00:07:50.755 --> 00:07:54.550
And he spent most of this later
part of his career here

00:07:54.550 --> 00:07:56.350
in the Mechanical Engineering
Department,

00:07:56.350 --> 00:07:58.300
from which he retired.

00:07:58.300 --> 00:08:00.880
And actually, he's too modest
to say it, but Professor

00:08:00.880 --> 00:08:06.000
Demkowicz, his PhD was for
Professor Argon, and Professor

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:08.630
Argon was one of Orowan's
students.

00:08:08.630 --> 00:08:10.760
So this is direct lineage.

00:08:10.760 --> 00:08:15.180
This is all very clear, so he
was the appropriate person to

00:08:15.180 --> 00:08:16.770
introduce dislocations.

00:08:16.770 --> 00:08:18.210
So what did Orowan do?

00:08:18.210 --> 00:08:21.840
Orowan came up with this idea
of an interruption.

00:08:21.840 --> 00:08:22.790
And how did he get it?

00:08:22.790 --> 00:08:26.770
It shows how to look
around and, in

00:08:26.770 --> 00:08:30.270
the world, see analogies.

00:08:30.270 --> 00:08:32.830
Now, we didn't have the powerful
electron microscopes

00:08:32.830 --> 00:08:33.760
then that we have today.

00:08:33.760 --> 00:08:36.900
This was in the 1930s, so people
didn't even agree on an

00:08:36.900 --> 00:08:38.980
atomic view of things.

00:08:38.980 --> 00:08:42.610
So people were thinking,
thinking, thinking.

00:08:42.610 --> 00:08:43.900
So this is the dislocation.

00:08:43.900 --> 00:08:44.540
You can see.

00:08:44.540 --> 00:08:46.930
Here, we have three rows of
atoms, now there's two rows of

00:08:46.930 --> 00:08:49.510
atoms. The middle
row stops there.

00:08:49.510 --> 00:08:51.750
And I'll show you what the
consequence of that is in

00:08:51.750 --> 00:08:56.040
terms of being able to shear the
crystal of lower values of

00:08:56.040 --> 00:08:57.720
applied stress.

00:08:57.720 --> 00:08:59.390
So that's the dislocation.

00:08:59.390 --> 00:09:00.260
You can see here.

00:09:00.260 --> 00:09:03.820
If you break this bond and then
propagate that through,

00:09:03.820 --> 00:09:05.180
you don't have to
shear them all.

00:09:05.180 --> 00:09:08.590
You break them one at a time.

00:09:08.590 --> 00:09:12.500
So Orowan came home one day in
Budapest, and the cleaning

00:09:12.500 --> 00:09:17.760
woman was moving the runner on a
hallway, the story goes, and

00:09:17.760 --> 00:09:20.120
she was about to move
the runner.

00:09:20.120 --> 00:09:22.700
And Orowan came up the stairs
and offered to help her, and

00:09:22.700 --> 00:09:25.440
she told him, get
out of the way.

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:26.320
Academic.

00:09:26.320 --> 00:09:30.140
And what she did, instead of
pulling the rug, she did what

00:09:30.140 --> 00:09:31.820
we see in the cartoon here.

00:09:31.820 --> 00:09:34.810
She put a little kink in the
rug, snapped her foot and

00:09:34.810 --> 00:09:38.400
propagated the kink and moved
the rug a half a foot down the

00:09:38.400 --> 00:09:40.710
hallway with minimal energy.

00:09:40.710 --> 00:09:43.720
Instead of having to pull the
rug with it's coefficient of

00:09:43.720 --> 00:09:47.150
fraction over three, four
meters, all she had to do was

00:09:47.150 --> 00:09:48.970
come up with enough energy
to make the kink and

00:09:48.970 --> 00:09:50.010
then stamp the foot.

00:09:50.010 --> 00:09:52.120
This person's really doing
it the hard way.

00:09:52.120 --> 00:09:52.750
I don't know.

00:09:52.750 --> 00:09:54.070
This guy must have
taken classes in

00:09:54.070 --> 00:09:55.030
chemistry or something.

00:09:55.030 --> 00:09:57.290
But see, all you've
got to do--

00:09:57.290 --> 00:09:59.310
once you get that kind
you just push

00:09:59.310 --> 00:10:01.600
and it'll go by itself.

00:10:01.600 --> 00:10:05.660
So Orowan said could this be a
metaphor for what's going on

00:10:05.660 --> 00:10:07.350
at the atomic level?

00:10:07.350 --> 00:10:09.070
And that's where it came up
with this idea of the

00:10:09.070 --> 00:10:10.320
dislocation.

00:10:12.080 --> 00:10:13.860
So there we have it.

00:10:17.370 --> 00:10:19.990
So where do we find
the dislocations?

00:10:19.990 --> 00:10:21.070
Where do we find them?

00:10:21.070 --> 00:10:21.790
So what is it?

00:10:21.790 --> 00:10:22.810
The dislocation--

00:10:22.810 --> 00:10:24.980
I keep talking about
it, what is it?

00:10:24.980 --> 00:10:29.920
The dislocation, this is, if you
like, it's a line defect.

00:10:29.920 --> 00:10:44.050
It's a line defect formed by
misregistry of atoms. And with

00:10:44.050 --> 00:10:51.005
the misregistry, that leads to
a reduction in bond density.

00:11:01.950 --> 00:11:05.800
And that broken bond is like the
hole, if you like, in the

00:11:05.800 --> 00:11:07.610
valence band.

00:11:07.610 --> 00:11:09.385
It can propagate very easily.

00:11:12.380 --> 00:11:14.840
We're going to learn a little
bit later in the lecture where

00:11:14.840 --> 00:11:18.650
we find dislocations and
how they contribute.

00:11:18.650 --> 00:11:22.700
But I want you to hold that
in near-term memory.

00:11:22.700 --> 00:11:23.070
OK.

00:11:23.070 --> 00:11:24.950
So we're going down
the list of the

00:11:24.950 --> 00:11:28.630
