00:11:31.950 --> 00:11:33.640
indicating--

00:11:33.640 --> 00:11:34.865
I think this is a
crummy analogy.

00:11:34.865 --> 00:11:37.320
It shows this caterpillar
moving by.

00:11:37.320 --> 00:11:40.200
Instead of moving all of its
legs, it causes this thing--

00:11:40.200 --> 00:11:42.980
I think this is a bad analogy.

00:11:42.980 --> 00:11:43.790
Just look down here.

00:11:43.790 --> 00:11:45.370
You see, you breaking this.

00:11:45.370 --> 00:11:48.440
And once you break this, you
just keep moving it along.

00:11:48.440 --> 00:11:51.030
Propagate the single broken bond
instead of breaking them

00:11:51.030 --> 00:11:54.200
all at once.

00:11:54.200 --> 00:11:58.100
I don't think the caterpillar
moves that way, anyway.

00:11:58.100 --> 00:12:00.950
It's cute, but it's wrong.

00:12:00.950 --> 00:12:03.030
This is a dislocation.

00:12:03.030 --> 00:12:04.490
I don't think it has anything
to do with mechanical

00:12:04.490 --> 00:12:07.100
behavior, but it's
a misregistry.

00:12:07.100 --> 00:12:07.890
So you can--

00:12:07.890 --> 00:12:11.060
these guys, they write the books
and they come up with

00:12:11.060 --> 00:12:12.590
this stuff and you study
it, and you're

00:12:12.590 --> 00:12:13.520
going, I don't get it.

00:12:13.520 --> 00:12:13.980
You know what?

00:12:13.980 --> 00:12:14.820
You shouldn't get it.

00:12:14.820 --> 00:12:15.770
Because this is crummy.

00:12:15.770 --> 00:12:17.020
It doesn't make any sense.

00:12:20.440 --> 00:12:23.690
How does that impact the yield
stress of the corn?

00:12:26.330 --> 00:12:27.980
Someday you could
write a book.

00:12:27.980 --> 00:12:29.560
Better one than this.

00:12:29.560 --> 00:12:30.580
