So now I'm going to take
this and blow it up.

00:38:25.590 --> 00:38:26.970
And what do I see here?

00:38:26.970 --> 00:38:30.010
I see atoms like so.

00:38:30.010 --> 00:38:31.920
I'm going to use that
hard-sphere,

00:38:31.920 --> 00:38:34.630
close-packed model.

00:38:34.630 --> 00:38:36.030
So here's the force.

00:38:36.030 --> 00:38:37.970
The force is vertical, agreed?

00:38:37.970 --> 00:38:39.960
We've got the mass and it's
pulling straight down

00:38:39.960 --> 00:38:41.110
according to gravity.

00:38:41.110 --> 00:38:43.330
So what's going on at the
atomic dimension?

00:38:43.330 --> 00:38:47.210
Because ultimately, this is
what we're working with.

00:38:47.210 --> 00:38:48.830
So what happens?

00:38:48.830 --> 00:38:51.370
One possibility, and don't
laugh-- this was actually

00:38:51.370 --> 00:38:52.180
suggested--

00:38:52.180 --> 00:38:56.100
when you cause extension in this
manner, you actually take

00:38:56.100 --> 00:38:58.600
some of these and you
can turn them into

00:38:58.600 --> 00:39:02.070
elongated atoms. No, no.

00:39:02.070 --> 00:39:03.710
That's no good.

00:39:03.710 --> 00:39:06.610
What in fact happens is slip.

00:39:06.610 --> 00:39:12.820
So the force-- in fact, let
me be more specific--

00:39:18.720 --> 00:39:25.850
the applied force is resolved
at atomic level.

00:39:30.080 --> 00:39:34.380
So what happens is that the
atoms slip over one another

00:39:34.380 --> 00:39:38.770
because they can slip along the
planes that have the least

00:39:38.770 --> 00:39:40.400
bonding between them, right?

00:39:40.400 --> 00:39:42.820
The chain is as strong
as its weakest link.

00:39:42.820 --> 00:39:47.130
So what will happen here is that
in order to affect the

00:39:47.130 --> 00:39:52.380
elongation, these will move
relative to one another along

00:39:52.380 --> 00:39:54.030
this slip plane.

00:39:54.030 --> 00:39:58.655
This is resolved at the atomic
level along slip planes.

00:40:01.610 --> 00:40:04.140
I'll write that larger
for the people way,

00:40:04.140 --> 00:40:05.510
way up in the back.

00:40:05.510 --> 00:40:06.760
I haven't forgotten about you.

00:40:13.870 --> 00:40:15.190
And what's the slip plane?

00:40:15.190 --> 00:40:17.620
How do I determine which
is the slip plane?

00:40:17.620 --> 00:40:20.080
The slip plane it's going to be
the plane that's strongest

00:40:20.080 --> 00:40:22.680
because it retains
its integrity.

00:40:22.680 --> 00:40:25.180
So which plane will
be the strongest?

00:40:25.180 --> 00:40:26.780
The one with the most bonds.

00:40:26.780 --> 00:40:28.730
And which plane has
the most bonds?

00:40:28.730 --> 00:40:32.430
The plane with the highest
number of atoms per unit area.

00:40:32.430 --> 00:40:34.480
And that's why we study
this stuff.

00:40:34.480 --> 00:40:37.280
Because now we know,
in an FCC crystal,

00:40:37.280 --> 00:40:41.720
which plane will slide.

00:40:41.720 --> 00:40:46.570
So in FCC, the high-intensity
plane is 1 1 1.

00:40:46.570 --> 00:40:49.980
So the 1 1 1 planes do the
sliding one over another.

00:40:49.980 --> 00:40:53.420
And they'll zigzag the way you
saw in the bubble wrap movie.

00:40:53.420 --> 00:40:59.890
They'll zigzag down, across,
across, across, But from a

00:40:59.890 --> 00:41:02.560
distance, it appears as the
thing is elongating.

00:41:02.560 --> 00:41:06.590
But at the atomic level, it's
zigzagging along the

00:41:06.590 --> 00:41:07.440
close-packed planes.

00:41:07.440 --> 00:41:09.240
Now I'm in a close-packed
plane.

00:41:09.240 --> 00:41:11.930
By the way, if I have the
highest density in the plane

00:41:11.930 --> 00:41:16.470
of the floor, can you understand
that orthogonal to

00:41:16.470 --> 00:41:19.132
the plane on the floor, I must
have the weakest density?

00:41:19.132 --> 00:41:20.880
All right, now I'm
in the plane.

00:41:20.880 --> 00:41:22.150
Which direction in the plane?

00:41:22.150 --> 00:41:23.820
Any direction?

00:41:23.820 --> 00:41:26.330
I'm going to push, I'm going
to push some pasta.

00:41:26.330 --> 00:41:29.990
I'm going to push uncooked
pasta or cooked pasta?

00:41:29.990 --> 00:41:31.740
Do you want to push on a rope?

00:41:31.740 --> 00:41:34.150
Do you want to push
on a broom handle?

00:41:34.150 --> 00:41:35.320
The stiff.

00:41:35.320 --> 00:41:38.460
So how do I determine, within
the plane, which direction is

00:41:38.460 --> 00:41:41.230
the stiffest direction?

00:41:41.230 --> 00:41:44.430
The one with the most atoms,
which is the close-packed

00:41:44.430 --> 00:41:45.900
direction when I'm
in the plane.

00:41:45.900 --> 00:41:48.670
So if I'm in the 1 1 1 plane,
which direction?

00:41:48.670 --> 00:41:50.250
The 0 1 1 direction.

00:41:50.250 --> 00:41:54.480
So this is direct line of
sight from the original

00:41:54.480 --> 00:41:55.790
crystallography.

00:41:55.790 --> 00:41:59.390
So that's how we get the slip.

00:41:59.390 --> 00:42:03.640
And in BCC the highest density
plane is 0 1 1 and so on.

00:42:03.640 --> 00:42:07.830
And the close-packed plane
simply means 1 1 1, because

00:42:07.830 --> 00:42:11.140
FCC is the closest-packed
structure, so that's a

00:42:11.140 --> 00:42:12.010
close-packed plane.

00:42:12.010 --> 00:42:14.910
Otherwise, they're planes
of highest density.

00:42:14.910 --> 00:42:15.860
It's a trivial--

00:42:15.860 --> 00:42:17.930
forget the last column--
it's pedantry.

00:42:17.930 --> 00:42:18.940
Forget it.

00:42:18.940 --> 00:42:21.050
I'm sorry I have it up there.

00:42:21.050 --> 00:42:23.370
So this is the slip system.

00:42:23.370 --> 00:42:30.270
So the slip system is
the combination of

00:42:30.270 --> 00:42:32.700
close-packed plane--

00:42:32.700 --> 00:42:38.370
or closest-packed plane--
close-packed plane and the

00:42:38.370 --> 00:42:41.160
close-packed direction.

00:42:41.160 --> 00:42:43.020
They all have close-packed
directions because we've got

00:42:43.020 --> 00:42:44.250
atoms touching.

00:42:44.250 --> 00:42:49.570
Close-packed direction.

00:42:49.570 --> 00:42:52.060
That's how it deforms. And then
if I get a dislocation in

00:42:52.060 --> 00:42:53.435
a close-packed plane, voom!

00:42:53.435 --> 00:42:55.180
Away they go.

00:42:55.180 --> 00:42:57.330
1/10 of the applied sheer
stress theoretical.

00:43:02.440 --> 00:43:07.770
So if you want to get it down
to a simple phrase, you can

00:43:07.770 --> 00:43:11.560
say, what causes slip?

00:43:11.560 --> 00:43:15.680
Atoms slip, dislocations
glide.

00:43:20.340 --> 00:43:22.480
But please don't think for
one minute-- listen to me

00:43:22.480 --> 00:43:24.410
carefully-- a lot of students
come away from this and they

00:43:24.410 --> 00:43:28.770
say, oh, I know why we
have deformation.

00:43:28.770 --> 00:43:30.220
Because of dislocations.

00:43:30.220 --> 00:43:32.680
No, no, no, no.

00:43:32.680 --> 00:43:34.600
Atoms will slip no
matter what.

00:43:34.600 --> 00:43:37.280
It's just that you're going to
pay a lot more to cause the

00:43:37.280 --> 00:43:38.450
deformation.

00:43:38.450 --> 00:43:46.760
The dislocations allow you to
have slip at lower cost.

00:43:46.760 --> 00:43:48.190
Yeah, this is good.

00:43:48.190 --> 00:43:53.260
And I think we're probably at
the point where I can show you

00:43:53.260 --> 00:43:56.620
the enormous consequences of
a three-dimensional defect.

00:43:56.620 --> 00:43:58.880
Why did the Titanic sink?

00:43:58.880 --> 00:44:02.030
It's a story of
three-dimensional defects and

00:44:02.030 --> 00:44:03.550
human greed.

00:44:03.550 --> 00:44:06.710
So this Tim Fecke at the
National Institutes of

00:44:06.710 --> 00:44:10.900
Standards and Technology with
an optical microscope and a

00:44:10.900 --> 00:44:12.430
rivet from the Titanic.

00:44:12.430 --> 00:44:14.710
And what I'm going to show
you in the rivet is a

00:44:14.710 --> 00:44:18.520
three-dimensional defect that
took the boat down.

00:44:18.520 --> 00:44:22.620
So this is the microstructure
and what they're doing is

00:44:22.620 --> 00:44:25.950
they're showing you a blow up of
this section of the rivet.

00:44:25.950 --> 00:44:28.450
Now, the rivet is
made of steel.

00:44:28.450 --> 00:44:31.130
Before I can explain to you
what's going on there, I have

00:44:31.130 --> 00:44:31.510
to show you--

00:44:31.510 --> 00:44:31.845
[MUSIC STARTS]

00:44:31.845 --> 00:44:32.900
PROFESSOR: Oh, shut up.

00:44:32.900 --> 00:44:34.300
[MUSIC ENDS]

00:44:34.300 --> 00:44:35.950
PROFESSOR: All right, so this
is how they made steel.

00:44:35.950 --> 00:44:39.470
Imagine this area the front of
10-250 as an open-hearth

00:44:39.470 --> 00:44:43.120
furnace, and I'm up to about
my knees in liquid iron.

00:44:43.120 --> 00:44:45.880
And on top of the liquid iron
is a slag made of silica,

00:44:45.880 --> 00:44:47.590
calcia, and alumina.

00:44:47.590 --> 00:44:50.380
It's the stuff when it
solidifies it makes something

00:44:50.380 --> 00:44:52.940
not too different from
window glass.

00:44:52.940 --> 00:44:55.800
But we use it for refining to
get some of the impurities out

00:44:55.800 --> 00:44:56.200
of the metal.

00:44:56.200 --> 00:44:59.180
And those impurities go up
into the slag phase.

00:44:59.180 --> 00:45:01.665
And to keep this thing it
about 1,300 degrees

00:45:01.665 --> 00:45:03.380
Centigrade, you've
got burners.

00:45:03.380 --> 00:45:03.970
Two.

00:45:03.970 --> 00:45:05.413
One at each end like dragons--

00:45:05.413 --> 00:45:06.400
[SOUND EFFECT]

00:45:06.400 --> 00:45:10.320
PROFESSOR: --blowing flame into
here for about 12 hours.

00:45:10.320 --> 00:45:11.510
12 hours.

00:45:11.510 --> 00:45:13.480
And that's what it took
to make a heat of

00:45:13.480 --> 00:45:16.060
steel back in 1910.

00:45:16.060 --> 00:45:18.690
This was made in Ireland, which
was, at that time, part

00:45:18.690 --> 00:45:21.460
of the United Kingdom.

00:45:21.460 --> 00:45:25.690
So on that day that they made
the heat of steel that

00:45:25.690 --> 00:45:28.550
ultimately was shaped into
rivets, evidently somebody

00:45:28.550 --> 00:45:32.320
became greedy, and instead of
waiting long enough for the

00:45:32.320 --> 00:45:37.120
slag to phase separate and form
a film on the surface of

00:45:37.120 --> 00:45:41.220
the metals, much like oil and
water don't mix, but you can

00:45:41.220 --> 00:45:44.880
shake them up in your salad
dressing application tool

00:45:44.880 --> 00:45:47.010
device and then pour
it on quickly.

00:45:47.010 --> 00:45:50.120
But if you let it sit
they phase separate.

00:45:50.120 --> 00:45:52.340
Well, somebody didn't allow
this to phase separate.

00:45:52.340 --> 00:45:54.350
They were told, pour
the heat anyways.

00:45:54.350 --> 00:45:58.680
So now you have globs of what
is the precursor to silicate

00:45:58.680 --> 00:46:00.620
glass in the metal.

00:46:00.620 --> 00:46:03.870
And now we take the metal and we
cut it into little billets

00:46:03.870 --> 00:46:06.750
and the billets are extruded
to form rivets.

00:46:06.750 --> 00:46:08.850
And then the rivets look
like this, where

00:46:08.850 --> 00:46:10.460
you have glass stringers.

00:46:10.460 --> 00:46:13.570
Three-dimensional defects,
impurity clusters,

00:46:13.570 --> 00:46:14.730
uncontrolled.

00:46:14.730 --> 00:46:16.960
What are the mechanical
properties of steel?

00:46:16.960 --> 00:46:17.930
Strong.

00:46:17.930 --> 00:46:18.770
Ductile.

00:46:18.770 --> 00:46:19.220
Tough.

00:46:19.220 --> 00:46:20.560
What does toughness mean?

00:46:20.560 --> 00:46:22.360
Impactability.

00:46:22.360 --> 00:46:24.510
When you say someone is tough,
it means they know how to take

00:46:24.510 --> 00:46:29.110
a hit, whereas hardness means it
takes enormous strength to

00:46:29.110 --> 00:46:30.440
cause deformation.

00:46:30.440 --> 00:46:31.850
They're very different.

00:46:31.850 --> 00:46:32.380
You know?

00:46:32.380 --> 00:46:34.010
You say someone is tough,
you mean one thing.

00:46:34.010 --> 00:46:35.780
You say they're strong,
it's different.

00:46:35.780 --> 00:46:37.920
You can be strong and
yet not tough.

00:46:37.920 --> 00:46:41.180
You can be strong and brittle,
so you can't take a hit.

00:46:41.180 --> 00:46:42.670
I know a lot of people
like that.

00:46:42.670 --> 00:46:43.840
That can't take a hit.

00:46:43.840 --> 00:46:46.100
Anyway, so enough about
the people.

00:46:46.100 --> 00:46:48.050
So here are the stringers.

00:46:48.050 --> 00:46:49.020
So what happened?

00:46:49.020 --> 00:46:50.150
What do you think
the mechanical

00:46:50.150 --> 00:46:51.260
strength of this is?

00:46:51.260 --> 00:46:54.190
If you have an impact like
so, instead of having the

00:46:54.190 --> 00:46:57.300
toughness to absorb the impact,
these things broke.

00:46:57.300 --> 00:47:00.450
This is like perforations on
a sheet of postage stamps.

00:47:00.450 --> 00:47:03.890
And so these rivets
were on the hull.

00:47:03.890 --> 00:47:06.090
And when the ship hit the
iceberg, what should have

00:47:06.090 --> 00:47:09.400
happened is there should have
an a small hole, the water

00:47:09.400 --> 00:47:13.760
would've taken, who knows, a
day or two to fill up, and

00:47:13.760 --> 00:47:15.740
there was plenty of time
to get rescue vessels.

00:47:15.740 --> 00:47:18.940
Instead, these rivets were
brittle, thanks to this.

00:47:18.940 --> 00:47:20.600
And so they just unzipped.

00:47:20.600 --> 00:47:21.930
Just pop, pop, pop, pop,
pop, pop, pop.

00:47:21.930 --> 00:47:24.970
Opened up a giant hole and
then took on the water.

00:47:24.970 --> 00:47:27.040
Now, did nobody check?

00:47:29.570 --> 00:47:32.310
Along the way, no inspection
of the steel?

00:47:32.310 --> 00:47:33.680
Nobody looked?

00:47:33.680 --> 00:47:36.130
The guys that we're doing the
riveting, they must have known

00:47:36.130 --> 00:47:38.310
the rivets were acting
strange.

00:47:38.310 --> 00:47:41.490
They must have broken a lot of
them just putting them in.

00:47:41.490 --> 00:47:42.770
But hey, it's not my job.

00:47:42.770 --> 00:47:43.480
Not my job.

00:47:43.480 --> 00:47:44.170
Not my job.

00:47:44.170 --> 00:47:48.370
No testing anywhere
along the way.

00:47:48.370 --> 00:47:50.840
What's shocking is
not human greed.

00:47:50.840 --> 00:47:52.110
That's as old as humanity.

00:47:52.110 --> 00:47:54.860
What's shocking is there
was no checks.

00:47:54.860 --> 00:47:59.020
So we have a different way to
make vessels like this today.

00:47:59.020 --> 00:48:01.400
But that's the story,
right there.

